<AI>“As AI becomes more capable,
democratic processes can be streamlined by allowing AI to pre‑filter policy options
and present only the most rational choices to citizens,
which improves efficiency without reducing democratic participation.”

① It reduces democratic participation. Not everyone uses AI, and the ways people use AI differ. They do not necessarily use it for seeking advice.
② Who determines whether they are “the most rational choices” for citizens?
Who certifies that the answers produced by AI are the most rational choices?
Who takes responsibility?
AI may hallucinate.
If the person responsible is malicious, they may distort what is considered rational for their own benefit.
③ What policy options are is vague.
Does it mean all policies, or only some of them?
④ The definition of “the most rational choices” is vague.
⑤ Who takes responsibility for AI’s decisions?
⑥ There is no transparency. AI is a black box.
⑦ AI only produces averages. It ignores diversity. Minorities will be left behind.
⑧ Being rational and “democratic processes” are not necessarily the same.
People may desire something irrational.
